# Frontend Code Quality + SOLID

Build small, testable, maintainable units. Optimize for readability and safe change.

## Core Rules

- Single responsibility per module/component; split files that do too many things.
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces/types/hooks), not concrete implementations.
- Keep UI components presentational when possible; move side effects and data access to hooks/services.
- Functions should be short, intention-revealing, and avoid hidden side effects.
- Prefer composition over deep inheritance or rigid base classes.
- Keep public APIs stable and minimal; avoid exposing internals.

## Reliability Standards

- Validate external input (URL params, API payloads, form values) before use.
- Handle async failures explicitly; never swallow errors.
- Return typed/domain-safe values instead of raw loosely-shaped objects.
- Add/keep tests for business logic and edge/error paths when behavior changes.

## Maintainability Standards

- Use descriptive naming for files, symbols, and props.
- Remove dead code, commented-out logic, and unused exports.
- Avoid large conditional trees; extract strategy/helpers when branching grows.
- Keep files cohesive; if a file exceeds reasonable size, split by responsibility.

## Quick Examples

```typescript
// BAD: component fetches, transforms, and renders all in one place
export function RevenueChart() {
  // network + business logic + rendering in same unit
}

// GOOD: data logic in hook/service, component focuses on rendering
export function RevenueChart() {
  const { series, isLoading, error } = useRevenueSeries();
  return <ChartView series={series} isLoading={isLoading} error={error} />;
}
```

```typescript
// BAD: swallowed error
try {
  await saveSettings(payload);
} catch (e) {}

// GOOD: explicit handling + propagation
try {
  await saveSettings(payload);
} catch (e) {
  logger.error("saveSettings failed", { error: e });
  throw e;
}
```
